=== There is massive investor uncertainty for offshore wind – tax credits and permitting issues key ===

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
&amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;_GoBack&amp;#34;/}}(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Mausolf**(%%), J.D. Candidate 2012, University of Detroit Mercy School of Law, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**’12**(%%) [Ashlyn N., NOTE: Clearing the Regulatory Hurdles and Promoting Offshore Wind Development in Michigan, 89 U. Det. Mercy L. Rev. 223, Winter, lexis]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)First(%%)__**, developers and investors confront … wind is not carefully planned, lawsuits can be waged, causing further delays. n94**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== Therefore the Plan: The United States Federal Government should amend the Coastal Zone Management Act to include an explicit mandate for offshore wind power development where appropriate and feasible on all U.S. coasts and require revisions to Coastal Zone Management Plans in accordance with this new mandate. The United States Federal Government should also extend and expand the Investment Tax Credit for offshore wind programs. ===

